                        </extent>
                                <condition>
                                    <p>Apart from f. 2 the leaves, having been used as binding, are
                                        damaged at the edges.</p>
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" writtenLines="35">
                                    <p>Written in long lines with 35 lines per page, except from f.
                                        3r having 32 lines. Traces of initials in coloured ink.</p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <accMat>
                            <p>An AM-slip in Árni Magnússon's hand, most possibly concerning this
                                fragment, is attached: <q xml:lang="is">Þesse 2. blöd feck eg 1716.
                                    af Monsr Þorsteine Sigurdzsyne. hafdi han<expan>n</expan> þau
                                    feinged nord<expan>ur</expan> i landi, en<expan>n</expan> eigi i
                                    Austfiördum. han<expan>n</expan> tok þau med ser fra Islandi
                                    1715. og gaf mier sem sagt er. Eru, sem mier synest, ur <hi rend="underline">Sögu Petrs Postula</hi>.</q> Another hand
                                has added: <q xml:lang="da">Hører til 655 Fragm. XVIA (?).</q>
                     </p>
                        </accMat>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin notBefore="1225" notAfter="1250" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">
                            <p>Written in Iceland. <name type="person" key="KriKaa001">Kålund</name> (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="KKKat">Katalog over Den
                                        Arnamagnæanske Håndskriftsamling</ref>
                                </bibl>) dated it the thirteenth century, whereas <name type="person" key="HreBen001">Hreinn Benediktsson</name> (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="IHFol2">Hreinn Benediktsson
                                        1965</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="pages">xliv</biblScope>
                                </bibl>) later agreed with <name type="person" key="KonGis001">Konráð
                                    Gislason</name> (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="KGFrumparta">Konráð Gíslason
                                        1846</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="pages">lxxxv</biblScope>
                                </bibl>) in dating it to the second half of the thirteenth
                                century.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>According to the AM-slip concerning <title>Pétrs saga postola</title>
                                this part of the manuscript belonged to <name type="person" key="ThoSig004">Þorsteinn Sigurðsson</name>. He once got it from
                                    <name type="place">Northern Iceland</name>, but not from <name type="place">Austfjörður</name>. The history of <title>Páls saga
                                    postola</title> is unknown.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>From the AM-slip telling only the story of <title>Pétrs saga
                                    postola</title> it can be infered that <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> acquired the two sagas
                                seperately. Árni got <title>Pétrs saga postola</title> from
                                Þorsteinn Sigurðsson in <date>1716</date>. The acquisition of
                                    <title>Páls saga postola</title> is unknown.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
